<node id="C5598">
<data key="n_label">Anal Paget Disease</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Neoplastic Process</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C1332274</data>
<data key="n_definition">A slowly spreading, erythematous eczematoid plaque in the anal region. Histologically, the basal part or whole thickness of the squamous epithelium is infiltrated by large cells with abundant pale cytoplasm and large nuclei. Half of the cases are associated with an internal malignancy, most often a colorectal adenocarcinoma. The other half of the cases, have a high local recurrence rate and they may become invasive (WHO).</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Anal Paget Disease|Anal Paget's Disease|Paget Disease of the Anus|Paget's Disease of Anus|Paget's Disease of the Anus</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C5598</data>
</node>
<node id="C36113">
<data key="n_label">Anaplastic Lesion</data>
