<node id="C43612">
<data key="n_label">Hepatobiliary System</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Anatomic Site</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Anatomy</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Anatomical Structure</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C1711359</data>
<data key="n_definition">Having to do with the liver, bile ducts, and/or gallbladder. | The body system that includes the liver, gallbladder, and associated ducts. | The liver, gallbladder, and associated ducts, considered collectively.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">hepatobiliary|Hepatobiliary System|HEPATOBILIARY SYSTEM</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C43612</data>
</node>
<node id="C66950">
<data key="n_label">Hepatoid Adenocarcinoma</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Neoplastic Process</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C1266090</data>
<data key="n_definition">An adenocarcinoma with morphologic characteristics similar to hepatocellular carcinoma, arising from an anatomic site other than the liver.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Hepatoid Adenocarcinoma|Hepatoid adenocarcinoma|Hepatoid carcinoma|Hepatoid Carcinoma</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C66950</data>
</node>
<node id="C165470">
<data key="n_label">Hereditary Colorectal Cancer Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Disease or Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui"></data>
<data key="n_definition">A group of hereditary neoplastic syndromes that affect the colon and rectum. Included in this grouping are hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer (HNPCCC) , familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP), and the hamartomatous polyposis syndromes.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Hereditary Colorectal Cancer Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C165470</data>
</node>
<node id="C120084">
<data key="n_label">Hereditary Colorectal Cancer Type X</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Disease or Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C3896578</data>
<data key="n_definition">Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer syndrome characterized by the absence of germline mutations in DNA mismatch-repair genes.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Familial Colorectal Cancer Type X|FCCTX|Hereditary Colorectal Cancer Type X</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C120084</data>
</node>
<node id="C54062">
<data key="n_label">Hereditary Lesion</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Finding/Clinical Attribute</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Phenotype/finding</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Finding</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C1708351</data>
<data key="n_definition">A pathologic process inherited in a familial pattern.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Hereditary Lesion</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C54062</data>
</node>
<node id="C9479">
<data key="n_label">Hereditary Malignant Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Neoplastic Process</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C1333600</data>
<data key="n_definition">Cancer that occurs in families more often than would be expected by chance. These cancers often occur at an early age, and may indicate the presence of a gene mutation that increases the risk of cancer. They may also be a sign of shared environmental or lifestyle factors. | Malignant neoplasms occurring in families at a rate greater than that expected by chance and caused by germline mutations in a specific gene.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">familial cancer|Familial Cancer|Familial Malignant Neoplasm|Hereditary Cancer|Hereditary Malignant Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C9479</data>
</node>
<node id="C220637">
<data key="n_label">Hereditary Mixed Polyposis Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Disease or Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui"></data>
<data key="n_definition">A rare autosomal dominant colorectal neoplasm predisposition syndrome caused by duplications in the regulatory region upstream of the GREM1 gene. It is characterized by the development of colorectal polyps of different histologies, individual colorectal polyps that contain components of more than one histological type, and a predisposition to colorectal adenocarcinoma.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Hereditary Mixed Polyposis Syndrome|HMPS</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C220637</data>
</node>
<node id="C120083">
<data key="n_label">Hereditary Nonpolyposis Colorectal Cancer Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Disease or Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C0009405</data>
<data key="n_definition">An inherited disorder in which affected individuals have a higher-than-normal chance of developing colorectal cancer and certain other types of cancer, often before the age of 50. | An inherited syndrome characterized by the development of several cancers, particularly colon and rectal cancers. It includes Lynch syndrome which is associated with germline mutations in DNA mismatch-repair genes and familial colorectal cancer type X which is characterized by the absence of germline mutations in DNA mismatch-repair genes.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Familial Nonpolyposis Colorectal Cancer Syndrome|Hereditary Non-polyposis Colon Cancer|hereditary nonpolyposis colon cancer|Hereditary Nonpolyposis Colorectal Cancer|Hereditary Nonpolyposis Colorectal Cancer (HNPCC)|Hereditary Nonpolyposis Colorectal Cancer Syndrome|HNPCC</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C120083</data>
</node>
<node id="C14158">
<data key="n_label">High Grade</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Terminology/Data Model</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Terminology/data model</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Classification</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui"></data>
<data key="n_definition">A term used to describe cells that look abnormal under a microscope. These cells are more likely to grow and spread quickly than cells in low-grade cancer or in growths that may become cancer. | Used to describe tumor samples that exhibit poorly differentiated or undifferentiated cells. They are generally expected to be fast growing and aggressive.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">High|High Grade|high grade</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C14158</data>
</node>
<node id="C35960">
<data key="n_label">High Mitotic Activity</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Finding/Clinical Attribute</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Phenotype/finding</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Finding</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C1334022</data>
<data key="n_definition">The presence of a high number of mitotic figures in a malignant tumor sample. It is associated with a higher rate of tumor recurrence and distant metastases, and a shorter survival.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">High Mitotic Activity</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C35960</data>
</node>
<node id="C36493">
<data key="n_label">High-Frequency Microsatellite Instability</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Molecular Abnormality</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Molecular genetics</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Cell or Molecular Dysfunction</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C1512430</data>
<data key="n_definition">The presence of genomic instability associated with defective DNA mismatch repair in greater than 30% of the microsatellite instability (MSI) biomarkers in a tumor sample.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">High|High-Frequency Microsatellite Instability|Microsatellite Instability High|Microsatellite Instability-High|MSI high|MSI-H</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C36493</data>
</node>
<node id="C176985">
<data key="n_label">Histology ICD-O Morphology Code</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
