<node id="C12468">
<data key="n_label">Lung</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Anatomic Site</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Anatomy</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Body Part, Organ, or Organ Component</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C0024109</data>
<data key="n_definition">A thoracic organ that has variable lobation and is the primary respiratory organ of mammals. | One of a pair of organs in the chest that supplies the body with oxygen, and removes carbon dioxide from the body. | One of a pair of viscera occupying the pulmonary cavities of the thorax, the organs of respiration in which aeration of the blood takes place. As a rule, the right lung is slightly larger than the left and is divided into three lobes (an upper, a middle, and a lower or basal), while the left has two lobes (an upper and a lower or basal). Each lung is irregularly conical in shape, presenting a blunt upper extremity (the apex), a concave base following the curve of the diaphragm, an outer convex surface (costal surface), an inner or mediastinal surface (mediastinal surface), a thin and sharp anterior border, and a thick and rounded posterior border. | Respiration organ that deve...</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Lung|LUNG|lung|Lung structure (body structure)|Lung, NOS|Lungs|pulmo|Respiratory System, Lung</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C12468</data>
</node>
<node id="C6725">
<data key="n_label">Lynch 1 Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Disease or Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C2674962</data>
<data key="n_definition">A rare genetic neoplastic syndrome with an autosomal dominant pattern of inheritance but incomplete penetrance. It is associated with a greater than 70 % risk of developing colorectal carcinoma. It is caused by a mutation in one of the mismatch repair genes: MSH2, MLH1, MSH6 or PMS2. It usually manifests at age 50 or younger with multiple synchronous or metachronous colorectal carcinomas. Clinical course is rapidly progressive. Prognosis is variable with a high risk for the development of additional colorectal carcinomas. However, survival is significantly better than non-HNPCC carcinomas of equivalent stage.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Familial Non-Polyposis Colon Cancer Type 1|Hereditary Non-Polyposis Colon Cancer Type 1|Hereditary Nonpolyposis Colorectal Cancer Type 1|HNPCC1|Lynch 1 Syndrome|Lynch Syndrome 1|Lynch Syndrome I</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C6725</data>
</node>
<node id="C6726">
<data key="n_label">Lynch 2 Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Disease or Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C1333991</data>
<data key="n_definition">A rare genetic neoplastic syndrome with an autosomal dominant pattern of inheritance but incomplete penetrance. It is associated with an inherited risk for malignancy, in particular, colorectal, endometrial or gastric carcinoma. It is caused by mutations in one of the mismatch repair genes: MSH2, MLH1, MSH6 or PMS2. It usually manifests at age 50 or younger with multiple synchronous or metachronous proximal colonic or extracolonic cancers. Clinical course is rapidly progressive. Prognosis is variable with high risk for development of gastrointestinal, reproductive or urinary tract cancer. However, survival is significantly better than non-HNPCC carcinomas of equivalent stage.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Familial Non-Polyposis Colon Cancer Type 2|Hereditary Non-Polyposis Colon Cancer Type 2|Hereditary Nonpolyposis Colorectal Cancer Type 2|HNPCC2|Lynch 2 Syndrome|Lynch Syndrome 2|Lynch Syndrome II</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C6726</data>
</node>
<node id="C8494">
<data key="n_label">Lynch Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Disease or Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C1333990</data>
<data key="n_definition">An autosomal dominant hereditary neoplastic syndrome characterized by the development of colorectal carcinoma and a high risk of developing endometrial carcinoma, gastric carcinoma, ovarian carcinoma, renal pelvis carcinoma, and small intestinal carcinoma. Patients often develop colorectal carcinomas at an early age (mean, 45 years). In the majority of the cases the lesions arise from the proximal colon. At the molecular level, high-frequency microsatellite instability is present.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Familial Non-Polyposis Colon Cancer (hMSH2, hMLH1, hPMS1, hPMS2)|Hereditary Colorectal Endometrial Cancer Syndrome|Hereditary Defective Mismatch Repair Syndrome|Hereditary Non-Polyposis Colon Cancer (hMSH2, hMLH1, hPMS1, hPMS2)|Hereditary Nonpolyposis Colon Cancer (hMSH2, hMLH1, hPMS1, hPMS2)|Lynch Syndrome|Lynch syndrome</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C8494</data>
</node>
<node id="C221744">
<data key="n_label">MBD4-Associated Neoplasia Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Disease or Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C5774186</data>
<data key="n_definition">A syndrome inherited in an autosomal recessive manner and caused by germline mutations in MBD4 gene. It is characterized by the presence of multiple colorectal adenomatous polyps and an increased risk of developing colorectal cancer, acute myeloid leukemia, and uveal melanoma.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">MANS|MBD4-Associated Neoplasia Syndrome</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C221744</data>
</node>
