<data key="n_umls_cui">C0007130</data>
<data key="n_definition">A type of cancer that begins in cells that line certain internal organs and produce mucin (the main component of mucus). | An adenocarcinoma comprising neoplastic glandular cells containing intracytoplasmic mucin. | An invasive adenocarcinoma composed of malignant glandular cells that contain intracytoplasmic mucin. Often, the infiltrating glandular structures are associated with mucoid stromal formation. It may arise from the large and small intestine, appendix, stomach, lung, ovary, breast, corpus uteri, cervix, vagina, and salivary gland.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">ADENOCARCINOMA, MUCINOUS, MALIGNANT|Colloid Adenocarcinoma|Colloid adenocarcinoma|Colloid Carcinoma|Colloid carcinoma|Gelatinous Adenocarcinoma|Gelatinous adenocarcinoma|Gelatinous Carcinoma|Gelatinous carcinoma|Mucinous Adenocarcinoma|Mucinous adenocarcinoma|Mucinous Carcinoma|Mucinous carcinoma|mucinous carcinoma|Mucoid Adenocarcinoma|Mucoid adenocarcinoma|Mucoid Carcinoma|Mucoid carcinoma|Mucous Adenocarcinoma|Mucous adenocarcinoma|Mucous Carcinoma|Mucous carcinoma</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C26712</data>
