<node id="C12384">
<data key="n_label">Sigmoid Colon</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Anatomic Site</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Anatomy</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Body Part, Organ, or Organ Component</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C0227391</data>
<data key="n_definition">The S-shaped section of the colon that connects to the rectum. | The part of the large intestine that is closest to the rectum and anus. It forms a loop that averages about 40 cm. in length, and normally lies within the pelvis, but on account of its freedom of movement it is liable to be displaced into the abdominal cavity. | The portion of the colon that connects to the descending colon above and the rectum below. | The portion of the colon that connects to the descending colon above and the rectum below. (NCI)</data>
<data key="n_aliases">COLON, SIGMOID|Sigmoid Colon|Sigmoid colon|sigmoid colon|Sigmoid colon structure (body structure)</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C12384</data>
</node>
<node id="C36777">
<data key="n_label">Signet Ring Adenocarcinoma Cell</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Cell</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Pathology/cytology</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Cell</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C1522040</data>
<data key="n_definition">A malignant glandular cell containing cytoplasmic mucin. The presence of mucin pushes the nucleus of the cell to the periphery, assuming a configuration resembling a signet ring.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Signet Ring Adenocarcinoma Cell|Signet Ring Malignant Glandular Cell|Signet-Ring Adenocarcinoma Cell</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C36777</data>
</node>
<node id="C3774">
<data key="n_label">Signet Ring Cell Adenocarcinoma</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Neoplastic Process</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C0206696</data>
<data key="n_definition">A highly malignant type of cancer typically found in glandular cells that line the digestive organs. The cells resemble signet rings when examined under a microscope. | A usually aggressive, poorly differentiated invasive adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells in which the nucleus is pressed to one side by the presence of intracytoplasmic mucus. It may arise from the stomach, small and large intestine, ampulla of Vater, appendix, gallbladder, pancreas, lung, bladder, breast, and prostate gland.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Signet Ring Cell Adenocarcinoma|Signet ring cell adenocarcinoma|Signet Ring Cell Carcinoma|Signet ring cell carcinoma|signet ring cell carcinoma|Signet-Ring Cell Carcinoma</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C3774</data>
</node>
<node id="C9292">
<data key="n_label">Solid Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Neoplastic Process</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C0280100</data>
<data key="n_definition">A benign or malignant neoplasm arising from tissues that do not include fluid areas. Representative examples include epithelial neoplasms (e.g. lung carcinoma, prostate carcinoma, breast carcinoma, colon carcinoma), and neoplasms arising from the soft tissues and bones (e.g. leiomyosarcoma, liposarcoma, chondrosarcoma, osteosarcoma). Neoplasms originating from the blood or bone marrow (leukemias and myeloproliferative disorders) are not considered solid tumors. | Abnormal mass of tissue that usually does not contain cysts or liquid areas. Solid tumors may be benign (not cancerous), or malignant (cancerous). Different types of solid tumors are named for the type of cells that form them. If tumors are associated with those under the term cancer, these terms should be used. | An abnormal mass of tissue that usually does not contain cysts or liquid areas. Solid tumors may be benign (not c...</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Solid Neoplasm|Solid Tumor|solid tumor|Solid tumor, NOS|Solid Tumour</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C9292</data>
</node>
<node id="C2929">
<data key="n_label">Squamous Cell Carcinoma</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Associated Disease/Neoplasm</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Associated conditions</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Neoplastic Process</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C3151392</data>
<data key="n_definition">A carcinoma arising from squamous epithelial cells. Morphologically, it is characterized by the proliferation of atypical, often pleomorphic squamous cells. Squamous cell carcinomas are graded by the degree of cellular differentiation as well, moderately, or poorly differentiated. Well differentiated carcinomas are usually associated with keratin production and the presence of intercellular bridges between adjacent cells. Representative examples are lung squamous cell carcinoma, skin squamous cell carcinoma, and cervical squamous cell carcinoma. | A malignant neoplasm arising from squamous epithelial cells. | Cancer that begins in squamous cells, which are thin, flat cells that look like fish scales. Squamous cells are found in the tissue that forms the surface of the skin, the lining of the hollow organs of the body, and the passages of the respiratory and digestive tracts.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">CARCINOMA, SQUAMOUS CELL, MALIGNANT|Epidermoid Carcinoma|epidermoid carcinoma|Epidermoid carcinoma, NOS|Epidermoid Cell Cancer|Malignant Epidermoid Cell Neoplasm|Malignant Epidermoid Cell Tumor|Malignant Squamous Cell Neoplasm|Malignant Squamous Cell Tumor|SCC|Squamous Carcinoma|Squamous carcinoma|Squamous Cell Cancer|Squamous Cell Carcinoma|squamous cell carcinoma|Squamous Cell Carcinoma, conventional|Squamous cell carcinoma, NOS|Squamous Cell Epithelioma|Squamous cell epithelioma</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C2929</data>
</node>
<node id="C38770">
<data key="n_label">Squamous Differentiation</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Finding/Clinical Attribute</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Phenotype/finding</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Finding</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C1519494</data>
<data key="n_definition">A microscopic finding indicating the presence of cells with squamous differentiation in a tumor sample.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Squamous Differentiation</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C38770</data>
</node>
<node id="C28051">
<data key="n_label">Stage 0</data>
<data key="n_node_kind">Entity</data>
<data key="n_in_colorectal_tree">N</data>
<data key="n_category">Finding/Clinical Attribute</data>
<data key="n_research_axis">Phenotype/finding</data>
<data key="n_semantic_types">Clinical Attribute</data>
<data key="n_umls_cui">C0441763</data>
<data key="n_definition">Cancer confined to the epithelium without invasion of the basement membrane.</data>
<data key="n_aliases">Stage 0</data>
<data key="n_nci_url">https://ncit.nci.nih.gov/ncitbrowser/ConceptReport.jsp?dictionary=NCI_Thesaurus&amp;ns=ncit&amp;code=C28051</data>
